# Performance Standard

## Purpose

Define performance targets, monitoring, and optimization standards for the enterprise e-commerce platform.

Performance directly impacts conversion — slow checkout loses sales.

---

## Service Level Objectives (SLOs)

### API Response Times (p95)

| Endpoint Category | Target | Alert Threshold |
|-------------------|--------|-----------------|
| Catalog read (product list) | < 100ms | > 200ms |
| Product detail | < 50ms | > 150ms |
| Cart operations | < 100ms | > 250ms |
| Checkout session | < 200ms | > 500ms |
| Order history | < 150ms | > 400ms |
| Admin list views | < 500ms | > 1s |
| Health check | < 10ms | > 50ms |

### Frontend (Core Web Vitals)

| Metric | Target |
|--------|--------|
| LCP (Largest Contentful Paint) | < 2.5s |
| INP (Interaction to Next Paint) | < 200ms |
| CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift) | < 0.1 |
| TTFB (Time to First Byte) | < 800ms |

### Availability

- 99.9% uptime (8.7 hours downtime/year max)
- Payment webhook processing: 99.99%

---

## Frontend Performance

### Next.js App Router

- Server Components for catalog pages (no client JS for static content)
- Dynamic imports for checkout Stripe components
- Image optimization via `next/image` with CDN
- Font optimization via `next/font`

### Bundle Size

- Monitor bundle with `@next/bundle-analyzer`
- Lazy load admin dashboard
- Tree-shake unused shadcn components

### Caching

| Resource | Strategy |
|----------|----------|
| Product pages | ISR revalidate 60s or on-demand revalidation |
| Static assets | Cache-Control: immutable, 1 year |
| API catalog | CDN edge cache 30s with stale-while-revalidate |
| Cart/checkout | No cache — private, no-store |

### Data Fetching

- Parallel fetch independent resources
- Avoid waterfall: don't fetch product then variant sequentially if combinable
- Prefetch product links on hover (optional, measure impact)

---

## Backend Performance

### Database

Primary optimization lever — see `database/04-queries` and `database/03-indexing`.

- Connection pooling (no connection per request without pool)
- Query timeout: 30s default, 5s for catalog reads
- N+1 query detection in integration tests
- Keyset pagination for large lists

### Async I/O

- FastAPI async endpoints for I/O-bound operations
- Async SQLAlchemy sessions
- Do not block event loop with synchronous CPU-heavy work — use thread pool

### External API Calls

- Stripe calls outside database transactions
- Timeout on all external calls (10s default)
- Circuit breaker for degraded external service

---

## Caching Architecture

```
Client → CDN → API → Redis (optional) → PostgreSQL
```

### Redis Use Cases (Optional)

| Data | TTL | Invalidation |
|------|-----|--------------|
| Product detail | 5 min | On product update event |
| Category tree | 15 min | On category update |
| Session cart (alternative) | 30 min | On cart mutation |

Redis is cache — PostgreSQL is source of truth.

Never cache:

- Checkout session totals without invalidation on change
- Inventory counts during flash sales (or TTL < 5s)
- Payment status

### Cache Key Design

```
catalog:product:{id}:v{updated_at_unix}
catalog:category-tree:v{max_updated_at}
```

Include version in key to prevent stale reads without explicit invalidation.

---

## Inventory and Checkout Under Load

Flash sale patterns:

1. Pessimistic locking on inventory row (correctness over speed)
2. Queue excess requests rather than fail silently
3. Rate limit checkout initiation per IP/session
4. Pre-warm cache for featured products
5. Load test before event

Acceptable degradation:

- Catalog may serve slightly stale stock display for 5s
- Checkout must never oversell regardless of load

